label("$\sqrt{a^2 + b^2}$", (A + C)/2, NE);
[/asy]

We want to minimize the ratio of the square of the diagonal to the product of a side and the area.  This is like minimizing the ratio of the square of the hypotenuse of a right triangle to the product of one leg and the area of the triangle.

By QM-AM, the square of the hypotenuse is greater than or equal to twice the product of the legs.  Hence,
\[\frac{(\sqrt{a^2 + b^2})^2}{ab} \ge \frac{2ab}{ab} = 2.\]Equality occurs when $a = b,$ so the minimum value is $\boxed{\frac{4 \sqrt{ab}}{1}}.$

